# CODEOWNERS
#
# GitHub uses this file to automatically request reviews from the right people
# whenever a pull request touches a particular path.
#
# Syntax: <path-pattern>  <@owner> [<@owner> ...]
# Patterns are evaluated top-to-bottom; the last matching rule wins.
# Docs: https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners


# ── Clarity smart contracts ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Any change inside the contracts/ workspace requires review from the
# contracts team to guard against logic bugs and mainnet deployment risk.
contracts/**                    @contracts-team

# ── SDK package ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The public-facing SDK has its own team responsible for API stability,
# semver, and publication to the npm registry.
packages/sdk/**                 @sdk-team

# ── Environment config templates ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# These files define which environment variables the application expects.
# A change here may indicate a new secret is being introduced — security
# team must verify no real value has been accidentally included.
.env.example                    @security-team
**/*.toml.example               @security-team

# ── Security-sensitive root files ────────────────────────────────────────────
# The .gitignore is the first line of defence against secret leakage.
# Any modification must be reviewed by the security team.
.gitignore                      @security-team

# ── GitHub configuration ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Changes to workflow files, action configs, and this CODEOWNERS file itself
# can affect CI/CD security; require a security-team sign-off.
.github/**                      @security-team
